reviewText: This was...not a great way of delivering this information. The first 3 courses in the specialization had enough substance to them that the clunkiness of the teaching methods was fine, but for a course about soft skills and communication, this was not a good format. There were some good examples and insights, but it would be better served as a condensed 40 minute YouTube video without the awkward attempts to use the quiz and project structure.

Did you know that people who take this class are not exclusively CS undergrads? Perhaps a person who has a job but would like to expand her responsibilities to include more object oriented development might enjoy this course.  Perhaps that person already knows how to interview because she has a development role, but just not in Java.  Perhaps her company is even paying for this class.I think every other part of this specialization has been great.  But this part was painful.  I hated every mind-numbing moment of it and I felt terrible about my company paying for me to learn how to interview.  I wanted to learn programming in Java and this was not programming in Java.  If I had wanted to take a course on job interviews, I would have.
nothing in common with reality. nothing that can prepare for real interviewuseless loss of time
Complete waste of time. I could learn the interview skls anywhere.
There is a lot of fluff on this course. It doesn't engage much.

It's a bit too simple all of this. There is not enough depth in the course. No way I would give 71 $ for such an introductory material. The best part of the course are the additional resources lists. The good and bad examples are useful as well, but they are all too simple as well.The videos are good quality though and there is some information that is useful. If you are looking for a simple introduction / never seen an interview / have no experience with public speaking / have not taken many oral exams then this is for you.I rate this at 2 stars because I was expecting more. A lot more. "Mastering...".. really? More like "Not completely failing.."
